What is SWIFT Code?
The SWIFT (Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunication) Code is the internationally recognized standard form for the Business Identifier Codes (BIC) used to identify a bank. Each bank has its unique code that distinguishes it from every other bank, a crucial step for the secure transferring of funds between banks. Swift code is used primarily for international bank wire transfers, SEPA payments and sometimes it is also used by banks for exchanging messages.
SWIFT Code Format
Each SWIFT Code is a series of 4 codes. The first is the 4 letter bank code which is typically an abbreviated version of the bank’s name. Next is the 2 letter country code followed by a 2 digit location code which indicates where the bank’s headquarters are. The location code can be two letters or two numbers, but the first two parts of the code are only made up of letters. The final part of the SWIFT Code is an optional 3 digit number that indicates the particular branch of the bank. This last part can be a combination of letters and numbers as well.
 The length of the swift code is either of 8 or 11 alphanumeric characters depending on type of financial institution.
International Bank Wire Instructions
 For international bank wire one needs to provide following details:

Recipient Name
Recipient Bank Name and Address
Account Number of the Recipient
SWIFT Code
IBAN Code (Depends on country to country)

About SwiftCodeLookup.org
So how do you find accurate SWIFT codes? At SwiftCodeLookup.org, we make it easy for you to get the SWIFT codes you need. With our search engine, you can look up a bank’s SWIFT code or you can search by bank name or by country. In our database, you have access to 105,600 SWIFT codes for 3,567 banks across the globe.














